spec: ab3286
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__, __isub__, __imul__ dict-presence (in-place augmented assignment) for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__iadd__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __iadd__. In-place addition (__iadd__, +=) is the augmented assignment variant of __add__. abc types define no __add__ (confirmed false in wave 658), so __iadd__ is equally absent. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no arithmetic semantics — ABC += n is not a defined Python operation and ABC has no __iadd__. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); none of these capabilities involve in-place addition. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __iadd__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not numeric or arithmetic types. f += n is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__isub__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __isub__. In-place subtraction (__isub__, -=) is the augmented assignment variant of __sub__. abc types define no __sub__ (confirmed false in wave 658), so __isub__ is equally absent. abc.ABC has no numeric data model; ABC -= n is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta's entire capability is in class-hierarchy machinery; in-place subtraction is entirely absent. The function type does not define __isub__; f -= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "Key finding (__imul__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __imul__. In-place multiplication (__imul__, *=) is the augmented assignment variant of __mul__. abc types define no __mul__ (confirmed false in wave 658), so __imul__ is equally absent. Note: list defines __imul__ (list *= n repeats in-place), but abc types are not list subclasses and implement no sequence-repetition protocol. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no sequence, numeric, or in-place arithmetic data model. abc.ABCMeta handles abstract method tracking and class hierarchy; *= has no meaning for metaclass objects. The function type does not define __imul__; f *= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 665 (__rand__/__ror__/__rxor__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, and in-place augmented assignment dunder tested across 15 consecutive waves (652–666). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __iadd__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__iadd__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __iadd__.
# In-place addition (__iadd__, +=) is the augmented assignment variant of __add__.
# abc types define no __add__ (wave 658), so __iadd__ is equally absent.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no arithmetic
#   or numeric semantics. ABC += n is not a defined Python operation; ABC has
#   no __iadd__ to serve as an implementation.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. In-place addition has no role in ABCMeta's responsibilities
#   (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__).
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __iadd__. f += n is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors with no
#   arithmetic or in-place augmented assignment data model.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3286.iadd:
  description: "abc types __iadd__ dict-presence checks; wave 666"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3286

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3286001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__iadd__"], false]
    - ["ab3286002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__iadd__"], false]
    - ["ab3286003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__iadd__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __isub__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__isub__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __isub__.
# In-place subtraction (__isub__, -=) is the augmented assignment variant of __sub__.
# abc types define no __sub__ (wave 658), so __isub__ is equally absent.
# abc.ABC: no numeric or arithmetic data model; ABC -= n is not a defined
#   Python expression. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no
#   state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __isub__ for in-place subtraction. ABCMeta's
#   API surface (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__) has no
#   arithmetic or augmented assignment component.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __isub__. f -= n is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. The function type is tightly scoped to its role as
#   a callable descriptor with a display representation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3286.isub:
  description: "abc types __isub__ dict-presence checks; wave 666"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3286

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3286004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__isub__"], false]
    - ["ab3286005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__isub__"], false]
    - ["ab3286006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__isub__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __imul__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__imul__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __imul__.
# In-place multiplication (__imul__, *=) is the augmented assignment variant of __mul__.
# abc types define no __mul__ (wave 658), so __imul__ is equally absent.
# Note: list defines __imul__ (list *= n repeats the list in-place), but abc
#   types are not list subclasses and implement no sequence-repetition protocol.
# abc.ABC: a pure abstract base class helper with no sequence, numeric, or
#   in-place arithmetic data model. ABC *= n is not a defined Python expression.
# abc.ABCMeta: a powerful metaclass, but its entire power lies in class-hierarchy
#   machinery — not in operator overloading. ABCMeta *= n is not a valid Python
#   expression.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __imul__. Unlike some frameworks that use * as a
#   composition operator, CPython's built-in function type has no __imul__.
#   f *= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3286.imul:
  description: "abc types __imul__ dict-presence checks; wave 666"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3286

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3286007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__imul__"], false]
    - ["ab3286008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__imul__"], false]
    - ["ab3286009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__imul__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __iadd__, __isub__, __imul__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __iadd__: false for all 3.
# __isub__: false for all 3.
# __imul__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 665 (__rand__/__ror__/__rxor__).
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__,
#          __mod__, __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__, __and__, __or__, __xor__,
#          __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__,
#          __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__, __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__,
#          __iadd__, __isub__, __imul__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with
#   a display representation. All arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, and in-place
#   augmented assignment operators are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic,
#   bitwise, reflected, and augmented assignment dunder tested across 15
#   consecutive waves (652–666). Its power lies exclusively in class-hierarchy
#   machinery — not in operator overloading of any kind.
# abc.ABC note: ABC is a pure syntactic convenience for declaring abstract base
#   classes. It has no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides, and defines
#   no arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, power/shift, reflected bitwise
#   logical, or in-place augmented assignment protocol whatsoever.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

